<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-622-730  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 622 730.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  July 9 1990 v12 n28 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Stationery documents work like templates: allow copying withoutcorrupting original. (Finder in Apple's Macintosh System 7.0)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lach, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Apple Macintosh System 7.0 operating system offers severalenhancements that increase the degree to which users can customizetheir systems.andP;  Apple's reintroduction of the stationery documentconcept is one of these.andP;  If a user clicks on a stationerydocument, instead of the document itself opening up, a documentwith the same contents of the stationery document is created.andP;  Thesystem allows the user to specify which articles should beprotected in this way from corruption during multiple or frequentchanges.andP;  System 7.0's new labels menu has labels that correspondto each color of the Color menu so users can use the text label tosort icons and then see the label in text views.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs)System 7.0 (Operating system) (product development).andO;Topic:     Form OverlayDocument PreparationProduct DevelopmentOperating SystemsCustomizationCopying.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>